What does Nature pursue as the thing supremely desirable, what does she avoid as the ultimate evil? It is a subject on which the most learned philosophers disagree profoundly3 who then can think it de· rogatory to such esteem as each may assign to me, to investigate what is the highest good and the 12 truest rule in every relationship of life? Are we to have our leading statesmen debating such topics as whether the offspring of a female slave is to be con- sidered as belonging to the party who has hired her, Publius Scaevola and Manius Manilius upholding one opinion and Marcus Brutus the contrary (not but what such discussions raise nice points of law, as well as being of practical importance for the business of life ; and we read and shall continue to read with ⁴ pleasure the treatises in question and others of the same nature); and shall these questions which cover the entire range of conduct be neglected? Legal y handbooks no doubt command a readier sale, but philosophy is unquestionably richer in interest. However‚ this is a point that may be left to the reader to decide. In the present work we believe we have given a more or less exhaustive exposition of the whole subject of the Ends of Goods and Evils. The book is intended to contain so far as possible a complete account, not only of the views that we ourselves accept, but also of the doctrines enunciated by all the different schools of philosophy. 13 V.
